(lp4
VAlong the ancient path of the Monongahela River,
p5
aVBraddock, Pennsylvania sits in the eastern region of Allegheny County,
p6
aVapproximately nine miles outside of Pittsburgh.
p7
aa(lp8
VAn industrial suburb,
p9
aVBraddock is home to Andrew Carnegie's first steel mill,
p10
aVthe Edgar Thomson Works.
p11
aVOperating since 1875,
p12
aVit is the last functioning steel mill in the region.
p13
aVFor 12 years, I have produced collaborative portraits,
p14
aVstill lifes, landscapes and aerial views
p15
aVin order to build a visual archive to address the intersection
p16
aVof the steel industry,
p17
aVthe environment,
p18
aVand the health care system's impact on the bodies of my family and community.
p19
aa(lp20
VThe tradition and grand narrative of Braddock
p21
aVis mostly comprised of stories of industrialists and trade unions.
p22
aVCurrently, the new narrative about Braddock,
p23
aVa poster child for Rust Belt revitalization,
p24
aVis a story of urban pioneers discovering a new frontier.
p25
aVMass media has omitted the fact that Braddock is predominantly black.
p26
aVOur existence has been co-opted, silenced and erased.
p27
aa(lp28
VFourth generation in a lineage of women,
p29
aVI was raised under the protection and care of Grandma Ruby,
p30
aVoff 8th Street at 805 Washington Avenue.
p31
aVShe worked as a manager for Goodwill.
p32
aVMom was a nurse's aid.
p33
aVShe watched the steel mills close and white flight to suburban developments.
p34
aVBy the time my generation walked the streets,
p35
aVdisinvestment at the local, state and federal level,
p36
aVeroded infrastructure,
p37
aVand the War on Drugs dismantled my family and community.
p38
aa(lp39
VGrandma Ruby's stepfather Gramps
p40
aVwas one of few black men to retire from Carnegie's mill with his pension.
p41
aVHe worked in high temperatures,
p42
aVtearing down and rebuilding furnaces, cleaning up spilt metal and slag.
p43
aVThe history of a place is written on the body and the landscape.
p44
aVAreas of heavy truck traffic,
p45
aVexposure to benzene and atomized metals,
p46
aVrisk cancer and lupus.
p47
aVOne hundred twenty-three licensed beds, 652 employees,
p48
aVrehabilitation programs decimated.
p49
aVA housing discrimination lawsuit against Allegheny County
p50
aVremoved where the projects Talbot Towers once stood.
p51
aVRecent rezoning for more light industry has since appeared.
p52
aVGoogle Maps and Google Earth pixelations conceal the flammable waste
p53
aVbeing used to squeeze the Bunn family off their home and land.
p54
aVIn 2013, I chartered a helicopter
p55
aVwith my cameras to document this aggressive dispossession.
p56
aVIn flight, my observation reveals thousands of plastic white bundles
p57
aVowned by a conservation industry
p58
aVthat claims it's eco-friendly
p59
aVand recycles millions of tires
p60
aVto preserve people's lives
p61
aVand to improve people's lives.
p62
aa(lp63
VMy work spirals from the micro to the macro level,
p64
aVexcavating hidden histories.
p65
aVRecently, at the Seattle Art Museum,
p66
aVIsaac Bunn and I mounted this exhibition,
p67
aVand the exhibition was used as a platform to launch his voice.
p68
aVThrough reclamation of our narrative,
p69
aVwe will continue to fight historic erasure and socioeconomic inequality.
p70
aa(lp71
VThank you.
p72
aa(lp73
V(Applause)
